The study by Lindqvist and Östling examines the relationship between political polarization and the size of government, using the dispersion of self-reported political preferences as a measure of polarization. The research finds a strong negative association between political polarization and government size in democratic countries, but no such relationship in undemocratic countries. This correlation remains robust after controlling for variables like GDP per capita and income inequality.

